content.description: Connects the two "V3" Routes on the wall. Start on the "Parking Bloc Center" and make your way right through a mono pocket to a bomber right hand gaston. The crux is figuring out how to get to the sharp, but deep, pocket on the Arete climb. After getting to the big pocket, finish out up the Arete.

Start with your hands on the right most holds and your feet to the right as well. Bump left and swing to the lower ledge under the rock to set up for a high heel hook, and finish with one big move to the top.

I recommend a pad due to a rock being close to the fall area.

It can be easily cheated so try to follow the pictures.
content.location: This Boulder is located a little past the main Boulder and to the right.

content.description: The smaller boulder to the right of the big boulder. Many variations exist.

Direct start to the large overhanging dihedral which is the centerpiece of the crag. Start is just right of where the trail meets the cliff. Boulder problem start leads to easier climbing. Climb underneath large overhang and pull through dihedral that features two bolts. Finish with gear to 1.5" Go all the way to the top to share chain anchors with the routes to the left.

Left approach start to the large overhanging dihedral which looms above the whole cliff and is the centerpiece of the crag.  Bolts start slightly right of where the trail meets the cliff. A stick clip can be useful. Climb underneath large overhang and pull through dihedral that features two bolts. Finish with gear to 1.5". Go all the way to the top to share chain anchors with the routes to the left.
content.protection: bolts with a couple of pieces to 1.5"

content.description: Fun climbing. A bolted crux low leads to easier low angle terrain.

From the main cliff, scramble up to the far right to what is known as the "Arapiles Sector". This is currently the farthest route to the right. After the crux start, some of the most fun climbing in the county is to be found on steep gym-like jugs. Chain anchors with fixed carabiners top the route.
Classic route with two cruxes. If you climb through them, you will not need trad gear for higher. Great rock.
Mixed route

A very popular climb. Climb the bolts on the slab with a finesse move down low. Climb under an overhang and place a small micro cam in the muddy horizontal crack. Reach over the lip and climb a steep bolted face to the top. A classic finish on great rock. Chain anchors on top- but are situated a bit far back to facilitate  rope pulling, top roping or lowering.
content.protection: A bolted sport route with closely spaced bolts except for one micro cam placement in the middle that protects 25 feet of unbolted rock.
content.location: Just a few feet left of when the trail reaches the crag. Starts near a small tree/bush growing by the crag.

content.description: Two variations for this.
Two variations up high.  The easier finish is to the left to end at cold shuts.  The right variation goes through a steep dihederal.
content.protection: bolts. Left variation gear to 3'  Right, gear to 2"
